[src:tanstack-table/component-based-software-engineering] To find the right level of component granularity, software architects have to continuously iterate their component designs with developers.
[src:tanstack-table/component-based-software-engineering] Architects need to take into account user requirements, responsibilities, and architectural characteristics.
[src:tanstack-table/component-based-software-engineering] CBSE grew out of earlier paradigms such as structured programming and object-oriented programming, but it places greater emphasis on building software by assembling and integrating pre-existing components.
[src:tanstack-table/component-based-software-engineering] Unlike objects, which typically encapsulate both data and behavior, components are higher-level constructs that provide well-defined interfaces and can be deployed independently.
[src:tanstack-table/component-based-software-engineering] Component orientation underlies many modern software frameworks and architectural styles, including service-oriented architecture (SOA), microservices, and widely used frontend frameworks such as React, Angular, and Vue.
[src:tanstack-table/component-based-software-engineering] For large-scale systems developed by large teams, a disciplined culture and process is required to achieve the benefits of CBSE.
[src:tanstack-table/component-based-software-engineering] Third-party components are often utilized in large systems, raising issues of integration, licensing, and software quality.
[src:tanstack-table/component-based-software-engineering] The system can be designed visually with the Unified Modeling Language (UML).
[src:tanstack-table/component-based-software-engineering] Each component is shown as a rectangle, and an interface is shown as a lollipop to indicate a provided interface and as a socket to indicate consumption of an interface.
[src:tanstack-table/component-based-software-engineering] This graphical representation helps clarify the relationships and dependencies between components.
[src:tanstack-table/component-based-software-engineering] Component-based usability testing is applied when components interact directly with the end user, ensuring both functionality and user experience are preserved when components are reused or replaced.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] This feature is well established and works across many devices and browser versions.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] It’s been available across browsers since July 2015.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] The **`Array`** object, as with arrays in other programming languages, enables storing a collection of multiple items under a single variable name, and has members for performing common array operations.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] `Array` objects cannot use arbitrary strings as element indexes (as in an associative array) but must use nonnegative integers (or their respective string form).
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] Setting or accessing via non-integers will not set or retrieve an element from the array list itself, but will set or access a variable associated with that array's object property collection.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] The array's object properties and list of array elements are separate, and the array's traversal and mutation operations cannot be applied to these named properties.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] Array elements are object properties in the same way that `toString` is a property (to be specific, however, `toString()` is a method).
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] JavaScript syntax requires properties beginning with a digit to be accessed using bracket notation instead of dot notation.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] It's also possible to quote the array indices (e.g., `years['2']` instead of `years[2]`), although usually not necessary.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] The `2` in `years[2]` is coerced into a string by the JavaScript engine through an implicit `toString` conversion.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] Only `years['2']` is an actual array index.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] `years['02']` is an arbitrary string property that will not be visited in array iteration.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] A JavaScript array's `length` property and numerical properties are connected.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] Several of the built-in array methods (e.g., `join()`, `slice()`, `indexOf()`, etc.) take into account the value of an array's `length` property when they're called.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] Other methods (e.g., `push()`, `splice()`, etc.) also result in updates to an array's `length` property.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] Increasing the `length` extends the array by adding empty slots without creating any new elements — not even `undefined`.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] Decreasing the `length` property does, however, delete elements.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] This is explained further on the `length` page.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] Array methods have different behaviors when encountering empty slots in sparse arrays.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] In general, older methods (e.g., `forEach`) treat empty slots differently from indices that contain `undefined`.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] Iteration methods such as `forEach` don't visit empty slots at all.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] Other methods, such as `concat`, `copyWithin`, etc., preserve empty slots when doing the copying, so in the end the array is still sparse.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] Newer methods (e.g., `keys`) do not treat empty slots specially and treat them as if they contain `undefined`.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] Methods that conflate empty slots with `undefined` elements include the following: `entries()`, `fill()`, `find()`, `findIndex()`, `findLast()`, `findLastIndex()`, `includes()`, `join()`, `keys()`, `toLocaleString()`, `toReversed()`, `toSorted()`, `toSpliced()`, `values()`, and `with()`.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] Some methods do not mutate the existing array that the method was called on, but instead return a new array.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] They do so by first constructing a new array and then populating it with elements.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] The copy always happens *shallowly* — the method never copies anything beyond the initially created array.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] Other methods mutate the array that the method was called on, in which case their return value differs depending on the method: sometimes a reference to the same array, sometimes the length of the new array.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] The following methods create new arrays by accessing `this.constructor[Symbol.species]` to determine the constructor to use: `concat()`, `filter()`, `flat()`, `flatMap()`, `map()`, `slice()`, and `splice()` (to construct the array of removed elements that's returned).
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] The following methods always create new arrays with the `Array` base constructor: `toReversed()`, `toSorted()`, `toSpliced()`, and `with()`.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] Many array methods take a callback function as an argument.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] The callback function is called sequentially and at most once for each element in the array, and the return value of the callback function is used to determine the return value of the method.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] The current element being processed in the array.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] The index of the current element being processed in the array.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] The array that the method was called upon.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] What `callbackFn` is expected to return depends on the array method that was called.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] The `thisArg` argument (defaults to `undefined`) will be used as the `this` value when calling `callbackFn`.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] The `this` value ultimately observable by `callbackFn` is determined according to the usual rules: if `callbackFn` is non-strict, primitive `this` values are wrapped into objects, and `undefined`/`null` is substituted with `globalThis`.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] The `thisArg` argument is irrelevant for any `callbackFn` defined with an arrow function, as arrow functions don't have their own `this` binding.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] The `array` argument passed to `callbackFn` is most useful if you want to read another index during iteration, because you may not always have an existing variable that refers to the current array.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] You should generally not mutate the array during iteration (see mutating initial array in iterative methods), but you can also use this argument to do so.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] The `array` argument is *not* the array that is being built, in the case of methods like `map()`, `filter()`, and `flatMap()` — there is no way to access the array being built from the callback function.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] All iterative methods are copying and generic, although they behave differently with empty slots.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] In particular, `every()`, `find()`, `findIndex()`, `findLast()`, `findLastIndex()`, and `some()` do not always invoke `callbackFn` on every element — they stop iteration as soon as the return value is determined.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] The `reduce()` and `reduceRight()` methods also take a callback function and run it at most once for each element in the array, but they have slightly different signatures from typical iterative methods (for example, they don't accept `thisArg`).
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] The `sort()` method also takes a callback function, but it is not an iterative method.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] It mutates the array in-place, doesn't accept `thisArg`, and may invoke the callback multiple times on an index.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] The `length` is memorized before the loop starts.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] This affects how insertions and deletions during iteration are handled (see mutating initial array in iterative methods).
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] The method doesn't memorize the array contents, so if any index is modified during iteration, the new value might be observed.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] The code above iterates the array in ascending order of index.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] Some methods iterate in descending order of index (`for (let i = length - 1; i >= 0; i--)`): `reduceRight()`, `findLast()`, and `findLastIndex()`.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] `reduce` and `reduceRight` have slightly different signatures and do not always start at the first/last element.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] Array methods are always generic — they don't access any internal data of the array object.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] They only access the array elements through the `length` property and the indexed elements.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] This means that they can be called on array-like objects as well.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] The `length` property is converted to an integer and then clamped to the range between 0 and 253 - 1.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] `NaN` becomes `0`, so even when `length` is not present or is `undefined`, it behaves as if it has value `0`.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] The language avoids setting `length` to an unsafe integer.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] All built-in methods will throw a `TypeError` if `length` will be set to a number greater than 253 - 1.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] However, because the `length` property of arrays throws an error if it's set to greater than 232 - 1, the safe integer threshold is usually not reached unless the method is called on a non-array object.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] Some array methods set the `length` property of the array object.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] They always set the value after normalization, so `length` always ends as an integer.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] The term *array-like object* refers to any object that doesn't throw during the `length` conversion process described above.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] In practice, such object is expected to actually have a `length` property and to have indexed elements in the range `0` to `length - 1`.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] (If it doesn't have all indices, it will be functionally equivalent to a sparse array.) Any integer index less than zero or greater than `length - 1` is ignored when an array method operates on an array-like object.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] Many DOM objects are array-like — for example, `NodeList` and `HTMLCollection`.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] The `arguments` object is also array-like.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] You can call array methods on them even if they don't have these methods themselves.
