[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] The result of a match between a `RegExp` and a string can create a JavaScript array that has properties and elements which provide information about the match.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] Such an array is returned by `RegExp.prototype.exec()` and `String.prototype.match()`.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] For more information about the result of a match, see the `RegExp.prototype.exec()` and `String.prototype.match()` pages.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] Iterative methods do not mutate the array on which it is called, but the function provided as `callbackFn` can.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] The key principle to remember is that only indexes between 0 and `arrayLength - 1` are visited, where `arrayLength` is the length of the array at the time the array method was first called, but the element passed to the callback is the value at the time the index is visited.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] The following examples use the `forEach` method as an example, but other methods that visit indexes in ascending order work in the same way.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] Inserting *n* elements at unvisited indexes that are less than the initial array length will make them be visited.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] Deleting *n* elements at unvisited indexes will make them not be visited anymore.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] Because the array has shrunk, the last *n* iterations will visit out-of-bounds indexes.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] Deleting *n* elements at already visited indexes does not change the fact that they were visited before they get deleted.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] Because the array has shrunk, the next *n* elements after the current index are skipped.
[src:tanstack-table/global-objects-array] For methods that iterate in descending order of index, insertion causes elements to be skipped, and deletion causes elements to be visited multiple times.
