[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] The **`HTMLTableElement`** interface provides special properties and methods (beyond the regular `HTMLElement` object interface it also has available to it by inheritance) for manipulating the layout and presentation of tables in an HTML document.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] A `HTMLTableCaptionElement` representing the first `<caption>` that is a child of the element, or `null` if none is found.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] When set, if the object doesn't represent a `<caption>`, a `DOMException` with the `HierarchyRequestError` name is thrown.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] If a correct object is given, it is inserted in the tree as the first child of this element and the first `<caption>` that is a child of this element is removed from the tree, if any.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] A `HTMLTableSectionElement` representing the first `<thead>` that is a child of the element, or `null` if none is found.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] When set, if the object doesn't represent a `<thead>`, a `DOMException` with the `HierarchyRequestError` name is thrown.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] If a correct object is given, it is inserted in the tree immediately before the first element that is neither a `<caption>`, nor a `<colgroup>`, or as the last child if there is no such element, and the first `<thead>` that is a child of this element is removed from the tree, if any.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] A `HTMLTableSectionElement` representing the first `<tfoot>` that is a child of the element, or `null` if none is found.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] When set, if the object doesn't represent a `<tfoot>`, a `DOMException` with the `HierarchyRequestError` name is thrown.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] If a correct object is given, it is inserted in the tree immediately before the first element that is neither a `<caption>`, a `<colgroup>`, nor a `<thead>`, or as the last child if there is no such element, and the first `<tfoot>` that is a child of this element is removed from the tree, if any.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] Returns a live `HTMLCollection` containing all the rows of the element, that is all `<tr>` that are a child of the element, or a child of one of its `<thead>`, `<tbody>` and `<tfoot>` children.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] The rows members of a `<thead>` appear first, in tree order, and those members of a `<tbody>` last, also in tree order.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] The `HTMLCollection` is live and is automatically updated when the `HTMLTableElement` changes.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] Returns a live `HTMLCollection` containing all the `<tbody>` of the element.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] A string containing an enumerated value reflecting the `align` attribute.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] It indicates the alignment of the element's contents with respect to the surrounding context.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] The possible values are `"left"`, `"right"`, and `"center"`.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] A string containing the background color of the cells.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] It reflects the obsolete `bgColor` attribute.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] A string containing the width in pixels of the border of the table.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] It reflects the obsolete `border` attribute.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] A string containing the width in pixels of the horizontal and vertical space between cell content and cell borders.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] It reflects the obsolete `cellpadding` attribute.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] A string containing the width in pixels of the horizontal and vertical separation between cells.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] It reflects the obsolete `cellspacing` attribute.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] A string containing the type of the external borders of the table.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] It reflects the obsolete `frame` attribute and can take one of the following values: `"void"`, `"above"`, `"below"`, `"hsides"`, `"vsides"`, `"lhs"`, `"rhs"`, `"box"`, or `"border"`.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] A string containing the type of the internal borders of the table.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] It reflects the obsolete `rules` attribute and can take one of the following values: `"none"`, `"groups"`, `"rows"`, `"cols"`, or `"all"`.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] A string containing a description of the purpose or the structure of the table.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] It reflects the obsolete `summary` attribute.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] A string containing the length in pixels or in percentage of the desired width of the entire table.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] It reflects the obsolete `width` attribute.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] Returns an `HTMLTableSectionElement` representing the first `<thead>` that is a child of the element.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] If none is found, a new one is created and inserted in the tree immediately before the first element that is neither a `<caption>`, nor a `<colgroup>`, or as the last child if there is no such element.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] Removes the first `<thead>` that is a child of the element.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] Returns an `HTMLTableSectionElement` representing the first `<tfoot>` that is a child of the element.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] If none is found, a new one is created and inserted in the tree as the last child.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] Removes the first `<tfoot>` that is a child of the element.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] Returns a `HTMLTableSectionElement` representing a new `<tbody>` that is a child of the element.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] It is inserted in the tree after the last element that is a `<tbody>`, or as the last child if there is no such element.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] Returns an `HTMLElement` representing the first `<caption>` that is a child of the element.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] If none is found, a new one is created and inserted in the tree as the first child of the `<table>` element.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] Removes the first `<caption>` that is a child of the element.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] Returns an `HTMLTableRowElement` representing a new row of the table.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] It inserts it in the rows collection immediately before the `<tr>` element at the given `index` position.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] If the `index` is `-1`, the new row is appended to the collection.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] If the `index` is smaller than `-1` or greater than the number of rows in the collection, a `DOMException` with the value `IndexSizeError` is raised.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] Removes the row corresponding to the `index` given in parameter.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] If the `index` value is `-1` the last row is removed; if it is smaller than `-1` or greater than the amount of rows in the collection, a `DOMException` with the value `IndexSizeError` is raised.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] The `HTMLTableElement` interface provides some convenience methods for creating and manipulating tables.
[src:tanstack-table/htmltableelement] Two frequently used methods are `HTMLTableElement.insertRow` and `HTMLTableRowElement.insertCell`.
[src:tanstack-table/introduction] TanStack Table is a **Headless UI** library for building powerful tables & datagrids for TS/JS, React, Vue, Solid, Qwik, and Svelte.
[src:tanstack-table/introduction] The hardest parts of building complex UIs usually revolve around state, events, side-effects, data computation/management.
[src:tanstack-table/introduction] By removing these concerns from the markup, styles and implementation details, our logic and components can be more modular and reusable.
[src:tanstack-table/introduction] Building UI is a very branded and custom experience, even if that means choosing a design system or adhering to a design spec.
[src:tanstack-table/introduction] To support this custom experience, component-based UI libraries need to support a massive (and seemingly endless) API surface around markup and style customization.
[src:tanstack-table/introduction] When you use a headless UI library, the complex task of **data-processing, state-management, and business logic** are handled for you, leaving you to worry about higher-cardinality decisions that differ across implementations and use cases.
[src:tanstack-table/introduction] Understanding these subtleties will help you make the right decision for your application and team.
[src:tanstack-table/introduction] Component-based table libraries will typically supply you with a feature-rich drop-in solution and ready-to-use components/markup complete with styles/theming.
[src:tanstack-table/introduction] AG Grid is a great example of this type of table library.
[src:tanstack-table/introduction] Headless table libraries will typically supply you with functions, state, utilities and event listeners to build your own table markup or attach to existing table markups.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] In reference to books produced without a computer, pagination can mean the consecutive page numbering to indicate the proper order of the pages, which was rarely found in documents pre-dating 1500, and only became common practice c.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] 1550, when it replaced foliation, which numbered only the front sides of folios.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] All of these software tools are capable of flowing the content through algorithms to decide the pagination.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] For example, they all include automated word wrapping (to obviate hard-coded newline delimiters), machine-readable paragraphing (to make paragraph-ending decisions), and automated pagination (to make page-breaking decisions).
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] Today printed pages are usually produced by outputting an electronic file to a printing device, such as a desktop printer or a modern printing press.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] These electronic files may for example be Microsoft Word, PDF or QXD files.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] They will usually already incorporate the instructions for pagination, among other formatting instructions.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] Pagination encompasses rules and algorithms for deciding where page breaks will fall, which depend partly on cultural considerations about which content belongs on the same page: for example one may try to avoid widows and orphans.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] Some systems are more sophisticated than others in this respect.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] Before the rise of information technology (IT), pagination was a manual process: all pagination was decided by a human.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] Today, most pagination is performed by machines, although humans often override particular decisions (e.g. by inserting a hard page break).
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] "Electronic page" is a term to encompass paginated content in presentations or documents that originate or remain as visual electronic documents.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] This is a software file and recording format term in contrast to electronic paper, a hardware display technology.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] Electronic pages may be a standard sized based on the document settings of a word processor file, desktop publishing application file, or presentation software file.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] Electronic pages may also be dynamic in size or content such as in the case of HTML pages.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] When end-user interactivity is part of the user experience design of an electronic page, it is better known as a graphical user interface (GUI).
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] The number and size of electronic pages in a document are limited by the amount of computer data storage, not by the display devices or amount of paper.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] Most electronic pages are for either display (screen output) on a computer monitor or handheld device, or output to a printing device.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] PDF and some e-book file format pages are designed to do both.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] Most applications will print electronic pages without the need for a screen capture.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] However, not all software supports WYSIWYG printing of pages.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] Pages exclusively for screen output are more commonly known as screens, windows, interfaces, scenes, or cards.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] In the case of presentation software, electronic pages are known as slides.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] Electronic pages displayed on a web browser are often called web pages, regardless of whether they are accessed online via a web server on the World Wide Web, or stored locally offline.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] More accurately, such documents are named by the markup language that makes them displayable via a web browser, e.g.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] With dynamic web pages, pagination is used for such things as displaying a limited number of results on search engine results pages, or showing a limited number of posts when viewing a forum thread.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] Pagination is used in some form in almost every web application to divide returned data and display it on multiple pages **within** one web page.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] Pagination also includes the logic of preparing and displaying the links to the various pages.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] Pagination can be handled client-side or server-side.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] For client-side pagination, the content of each page is included in the HTML source code pre-loaded within the page, while server-side pagination requests each page individually upon navigation.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] Client-side pagination can be used when there are very few records to be accessed, in which case all records can be returned, and the client can use JavaScript or CSS to view the separate pages.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] By using AJAX, hybrid server/client-side pagination can be used, in which JavaScript is used to request the subsequent page from the server which is loaded and inserted into the Document Object Model via AJAX.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] Server-side pagination is appropriate for large data sets providing faster initial page load, accessibility for those not running Javascript, and complex view business logic, while client-side pagination allows navigating between pages without delay from a server request.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] Correctly implementing pagination can be difficult.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] There are many different usability questions such as should "previous" and "next" links be included, how many links to pages should be displayed, and should there be a link to the first and last pages.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] Also ability to define the number of records displayed in a single page is useful.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] In comparison to bottomless or infinite scrolling, pagination allows skipping pages and can be implemented with permanent links (as done with the `offset` URL parameter in the MediaWiki wiki engine), whereas infinite scrolling continuously displays material dynamically.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] Pagination is an approach used to limit and display only a part of the total data of a query in the database.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] Instead of showing hundreds or thousands of rows at the same time, the server is requested only one page (a limited set of rows, per example only 10 rows), and the user starts navigating by requesting the next page, and then the next one, and so on.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] It is very useful, specially in web systems, where there is no dedicated connection between the client and the server, so the client does not have to wait to read and display all the rows of the server.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] Today, all content, no matter which output medium is planned, predicted, or not predicted, can be produced with technologies that allow downstream transformations into any presentation desired, although such best-practice preparation is still far from universal.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] This usually involves a markup language (such as XML, HTML, or SGML) that tags the content semantically and machine-readably, which allows downstream technologies (such as XSLT, XSL, or CSS) to output them into whatever presentation is desired.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] This concept is known as the separation of presentation and content.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] This paradigm is now the conventional one in most commercial publishing, except to the extent that legacy and backward compatibility issues and budget constraints interfere, and to the extent that many of the people involved do not understand the topic enough to help build compliance.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] But the need to manually paginate has diminished as the technology for dynamic display and automatic pagination advances.
[src:tanstack-table/pagination] Also, there is less need to make a hierarchical distinction between pagination in print and pagination in electronic display, because the same underlying content will most likely be used for the latter exclusively if not for both display methods.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] A **table** is an arrangement of information or data, typically in rows and columns, or possibly in a more complex structure.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] Tables are widely used in communication, research, and data analysis.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] Tables appear in print media, handwritten notes, computer software, architectural ornamentation, traffic signs, and many other places.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] The precise conventions and terminology for describing tables vary depending on the context.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] Further, tables differ significantly in variety, structure, flexibility, notation, representation and use.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] Information or data conveyed in table form is said to be in **tabular** format (adjective).
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] In books and technical articles, tables are typically presented apart from the main text in numbered and captioned floating blocks.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] A **table cell** is one grouping within a chart table used for storing information or data.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] Cells are grouped horizontally (rows of cells) and vertically (columns of cells).
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] Each cell contains information relating to the combination of the row and column headings it is collinear with.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] A table consists of an ordered arrangement of **rows** and **columns**.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] This is a simplified description of the most basic kind of table.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] The elements of a table may be grouped, segmented, or arranged in many different ways, and even nested recursively.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] Additionally, a table may include metadata, annotations, a header, a footer or other ancillary features.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] The following illustrates a simple table with four columns and nine rows.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] The first row is not counted, because it is only used to display the column names.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] The concept of **dimension** is also a part of basic terminology.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] Any "simple" table can be represented as a "multi-dimensional" table by normalizing the data values into ordered hierarchies.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] A common example of such a table is a multiplication table.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] In multi-dimensional tables, each cell in the body of the table (and the value of that cell) relates to the values at the beginnings of the column (i.e. the header), the row, and other structures in more complex tables.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] The first column often presents information dimension description by which the rest of the table is navigated.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] Tables may contain three or multiple dimensions and can be classified by the number of dimensions.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] Multi-dimensional tables may have super-rows - rows that describe additional dimensions for the rows that are presented below that row and are usually grouped in a tree-like structure.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] This structure is typically visually presented with an appropriate number of white spaces in front of each stub's label.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] In literature tables often present numerical values, cumulative statistics, categorical values, and at times parallel descriptions in form of text.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] They can condense large amount of information to a limited space and therefore they are popular in scientific literature in many fields of study.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] As a communication tool, a table allows a form of generalization of information from an unlimited number of different social or scientific contexts.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] It provides a familiar way to convey information that might otherwise not be obvious or readily understood.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] For example, in the following diagram, two alternate representations of the same information are presented side by side.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] On the left is the NFPA 704 standard "fire diamond" with example values indicated and on the right is a simple table displaying the same values, along with additional information.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] Both representations convey essentially the same information, but the tabular representation is arguably more comprehensible to someone who is not familiar with the NFPA 704 standard.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] The tabular representation may not, however, be ideal for every circumstance (for example because of space limitations, or safety reasons).
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] Modern software applications give users the ability to generate, format, and edit tables and tabular data for a wide variety of uses, such as in: word processing and spreadsheet applications, presentation software, and in HTML or another markup language.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] Table cells are a key component in HTML and webpage building.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] A programmer may specify dimensions for a table cell, and use them to hold sections of webpages.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] A table cell in HTML is a non-empty element and is supposed to always be closed.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] There are two different kinds of table cell in HTML, namely: normal table cell and header cell.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] **<td>** denotes a table cell, the name implying 'data', while **<th>** denotes a table 'header'.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] The two can be used interchangeably, but it is recommended that header cell be only used for the top and side headers of a table.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] Furthermore, a table cell must be nested within a **<table>** tag *and* a **<tr>** (table row) tag.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] If there are more table cell tags in any given row than in any other, the particular **<tr>** must be given a colspan attribute declaring how many columns of cells wide it should be.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] By using the **rowspan** and **colspan** attributes, developers can combine multiple rows or columns, allowing them to design more complex and visually structured tables.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] Tables have uses in software development for both high-level specification and low-level implementation.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] Usage in software specification can encompass ad hoc inclusion of simple decision tables in textual documents through to the use of tabular specification methodologies, examples of which include Software Cost Reduction and Statestep.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] Database systems often store data in structures called tables; in which columns are data fields and rows represent data records.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] There are several specific situations in which tables are routinely used as a matter of custom or formal convention.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] A table of contents (or simply contents, abbreviated as TOC), is a list usually part of the front matter preceding the main text of a book or other written work containing the titles of the text's sections, sometimes with descriptions.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] Angles less than 45° are found on the left page, angles greater than 45° on the right.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] Cosine, cotangent and cosecant are found by using the entry on the opposite page.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] Mathematical tables are tables of information, usually numbers, showing the results of a calculation with varying arguments.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] Trigonometric tables were used in ancient Greece and India for applications to astronomy and celestial navigation, and continued to be widely used until electronic calculators became cheap and plentiful in the 1970s, in order to simplify and drastically speed up computation.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] Tables of logarithms and trigonometric functions were common in math and science textbooks, and specialized tables were published for numerous applications.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] In natural sciences, uses of tables include the periodic table in chemistry, and tide tables in oceanography.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] The periodic table, also known as the periodic table of the elements, is an ordered arrangement of the chemical elements into rows ("periods") and columns ("groups").
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] An icon of chemistry, the periodic table is widely used in physics and other sciences.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] It is a depiction of the periodic law, which states that when the elements are arranged in order of their atomic numbers an approximate recurrence of their properties is evident.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] The table is divided into four roughly rectangular areas called blocks.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] Elements in the same group tend to show similar chemical characteristics.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] Tide tables, sometimes called tide charts, are used for tidal prediction and show the daily times and levels of high and low tides, usually for a particular location.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] Tide heights at intermediate times (between high and low water) can be approximated by using the rule of twelfths or more accurately calculated by using a published tidal curve for the location.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] Tide levels are typically given relative to a low-water vertical datum, e.g. the mean lower low water (MLLW) datum in the US.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] In medieval counting houses, the tables were covered with a piece of checkered cloth, to count money.*Exchequer* is an archaic term for the English institution which accounted for money owed to the monarch.
[src:tanstack-table/table-information] Thus the checkerboard tables of stacks of coins are a concrete realization of this information.
[src:tanstack-table/tanstack-table] A headless table library for building powerful datagrids with full control over markup, styles, and behavior.
[src:tanstack-table/tanstack-table] TanStack Table ships TanStack Intent skills inside each adapter package.
[src:tanstack-table/tanstack-table] to add skill-loading guidance for your agent (Claude Code, Cursor, Copilot, etc.).
[src:tanstack-table/tanstack-table] The same CLI also exposes `intent list` to browse available skills and `intent load <skill>` to print one for inspection.
[src:tanstack-table/tanstack-table] Skills version with the library — your agent gets guidance that matches the version of `@tanstack/<framework>-table` you installed.
